<strong>REFERENCE LIST ENTRY</strong>
<br>
<br>
Add a reference list at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br>
<br>
Do not italicise the title of works that are part of a greater whole (e.g., journal articles 
and edited book chapters).
<br>
<br>
For works that stand alone (e.g., books, reports, webpages, and websites) italicise the title 
and capitalise using sentence case (the first letter of the first word only, in the main title 
and subtitle, is capitalised).
<br>
<br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	Organisation. (Year of publication). <em>Title of webpage</em>. Site Name. URL
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author and the site name are the same, omit the site name from the reference. 
If content is likely to change over time, include a retrieval date before the URL.
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	Organisation. (n.d.). <em>Title of webpage</em>. Site Name. Retrieved Month Day, Year, from URL
</blockquote>
<br>
If a date of the last update is available on the webpage and specifically refers to the content 
on the page, rather than the overall website, use the updated date in the reference (e.g., 
Year, Month Day of publication). Do not include the date of the last review, as this may not 
necessarily mean that content on the page you are citing has changed. When no date is available, 
use n.d. for &#8216;no date&#8217;.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	<span class="hover" title="Organisation">The Turning Page Bookshop</span>. 
	(<span class="hover" title="Year of publication">2020</span>). 
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of web page">Business profile</span></em>.  
	<span class="hover fake-aref" title="URL">http://www.theturningpagebookshop.com.au/</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
The URL is displayed as a hyperlink.
